    q: "What's the best coffee-to-water ratio for pour-over?",
    a: "Start at 1:16 by weight, which means 15.6 grams of coffee for every 250 grams of water. Push to 1:17 for very light, high-acid coffees like Kenya AA or Yirgacheffe to let the sweetness develop. Pull back to 1:15 if a coffee tastes thin or sour. Measure both coffee and water on a scale; volume measurements drift by 15 to 20 percent depending on grind and bean density."
  },
  {
    q: "Do I need a gooseneck kettle for pour-over?",
    a: "Yes if you care about consistency. The narrow spout lets you control flow rate and pour location, which directly controls how evenly water saturates the bed. A regular kettle dumps water, channels the bed, and produces uneven extraction. A basic gooseneck runs about $40. A variable-temperature electric gooseneck runs about $150 and removes guesswork around water temperature, which matters more for light roasts than people expect."
  },
  {
    q: "Can I use dark roast for pour-over?",
    a: "You can but it fights the method. Pour-over rewards clarity and acidity; dark roasts deliver body and bitterness that get amplified by the paper filter stripping fats. If you brew dark roast as pour-over, drop water temperature to 195°F, grind slightly coarser, and pull the brew shorter at around 2:45 to avoid extracting bitter compounds. You will still get a flatter cup than the same beans on a Moccamaster or French press."
  },
  {
    q: "How fresh do beans need to be for pour-over?",
    a: "Rest beans 7 to 14 days off roast, then use them within 4 weeks. Pour-over is the most punishing method for stale coffee because it relies on CO2 bloom for even saturation. Beans older than 4 weeks bloom weakly, channel the water, and taste cardboardy. Beans under 7 days off roast bloom so violently they overflow the cone and produce sour, underdeveloped cups. Check the roast date on the bag, not the sell-by date."
  },
  {
    q: "Is filtered water important for pour-over?",
    a: "Water is 98.5 percent of the cup, so yes. Use water with 75 to 175 ppm total dissolved solids and balanced calcium-to-magnesium ratios. Tap water with chlorine kills aroma; distilled water has nothing for flavor compounds to bind to and produces flat, hollow cups. A basic charcoal filter works for most municipal water. Third Wave Water sachets ($25 for 12) give lab-perfect brewing water if your tap is bad."
  },
  {
    q: "Which grinder should I use for pour-over?",
    a: "Burr, always. Blade grinders produce uneven particles that extract at different rates and guarantee a muddled cup. Hand grinders like the Timemore C2 ($70) or 1Zpresso JX ($165) beat most $200 electric grinders for filter-coffee grind quality. If you want electric, the Baratza Encore ESP ($199) and Fellow Opus ($195) are the entry points where pour-over actually starts working. Below $150 electric, buy hand."
  }
];

