<p class="body">Pour-over rewards a narrow band of coffees and punishes everything outside it. The method works best with light to medium washed single origins from high-altitude farms, where dense beans and clean processing produce the floral, citric, and tea-like cups the paper filter is built to deliver. It punishes heavy dark roasts (bitter, papery), weighty Sumatrans (the body collapses under filtration), and stale supermarket blends (no bloom, no aroma, no point). If you want a single recommendation that defines what pour-over is supposed to taste like, buy <a href="https://www.volcanicacoffee.com" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" style="color: var(--gold); text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 1px solid rgba(201,168,76,0.35);">Volcanica Ethiopian Yirgacheffe</a> and brew it on a V60 at 1:16. That is the benchmark cup the rest of the guide circles back to.</p>

<p class="body">The five picks below are all real coffees from real specialty roasters, ordered by how reliably they reward the method. After the picks, we cover brew technique, the three major filter formats (V60, Chemex, Kalita), and the mistakes that ruin even great beans. Read the <a href="/learn/single-origin-coffee-guide" style="color: var(--gold); text-decoration: none;">single origin coffee guide</a> first if you want background on why origin character matters before paying $22 a bag for a 250g cup.</p>

<h2 class="section-head">What makes a coffee great <em>for pour-over</em></h2>

<p class="body">Pour-over is a paper-filtered, gravity-fed, slow-saturation method. Every choice the brewer makes (grind, ratio, pour pattern, temperature) is in service of one outcome: clean, even extraction that lets the bean's origin character read through clearly. The paper filter strips lipids and fines that would carry body and silt, so what's left in the cup is acidity, aromatics, and sugar development. That is the lens through which to pick beans.</p>

<h3 class="sub-head">Light to medium roast</h3>
<p class="body">Light and medium roasts preserve the volatile aromatic compounds (esters, aldehydes, terpenes) that produce jasmine, bergamot, blueberry, and stone fruit notes. Dark roasts burn those compounds off and replace them with Maillard browning, which reads as chocolate, caramel, and at the dark end, char. Dark roast on pour-over tastes thin and ashy because the method strips the body that dark roast usually leans on. Stick to roasts where the bean's natural color is still visible: light brown, no oil sheen.</p>

<h3 class="sub-head">Washed processing</h3>
<p class="body">Washed coffees go through a depulping and fermentation step that removes all fruit before drying, producing beans with the cleanest possible flavor profile: pure varietal and terroir, no fruit-fermentation overlay. Natural-process coffees ferment in the fruit and pick up berry, wine, and tropical notes that are gorgeous on a French press but muddle under a paper filter. If you're choosing between two bags of the same origin, washed wins for pour-over nine times out of ten. The <a href="/learn/washed-vs-natural-coffee" style="color: var(--gold); text-decoration: none;">washed vs natural processing breakdown</a> covers why this matters at the cellular level.</p>

<h3 class="sub-head">High-grown beans (1,400m and up)</h3>
<p class="body">Altitude matters because slower cherry maturation produces denser beans with more concentrated sugars. A bean grown at 1,800m has roughly 30 percent more density than one grown at 800m, which translates to sharper acidity, more sugar development under heat, and better mechanical structure in the grinder (denser beans fracture more uniformly). Pour-over rewards that density because slow saturation gives the dense bean time to release sugars in stages.</p>

<h3 class="sub-head">Single-origin so character reads through</h3>
<p class="body">Blends are designed for body and consistency. A pour-over filter strips body and broadcasts character, so a blend ends up as the average of its parts (flat). Single origins broadcast one place, one farm, one varietal, so the brew reads like that place. Yirgacheffe should taste like Yirgacheffe. Kenya AA should taste like Kenya AA. Pour-over is the method that makes that distinction audible in the cup.</p>

