<h2 class="section-head">How to brew pour-over <em>that actually works</em></h2>

<p class="body">Great beans are necessary but not sufficient. The method below is the standard third-wave specialty protocol, scaled to a 250g brew (one large mug or two small cups). It works on V60, Chemex, and Kalita with minor adjustments noted in the next section.</p>

<h3 class="sub-head">Ratio: 1:16 to 1:17 by weight</h3>
<p class="body">For 250g of water, use 15.6g of coffee (1:16) for the default. For very light roasts or high-acid coffees like Kenya AA, drop to 14.7g (1:17) to let sweetness build. Always weigh both. Volume measures (tablespoons, scoops) vary by grind size and bean density and will throw your ratio off by 15 percent or more.</p>

<h3 class="sub-head">Water temperature: 200°F (195°F for very light)</h3>
<p class="body">Water at 200°F extracts the broad band of soluble compounds (acids, sugars, melanoidins) at the rate the method assumes. For very light roasts where the bean is denser and less developed, 195°F gives you a longer extraction window without scorching the surface aromatics. Anything below 190°F under-extracts and produces sour, hollow cups regardless of bean quality.</p>

<h3 class="sub-head">Grind: medium-fine, between table salt and sugar</h3>
<p class="body">Grind so the particles look like a mix of coarse salt and fine sugar (around 600 to 800 microns on a precision burr). Too coarse and water rushes through, producing a sour, weak, under-extracted cup. Too fine and the bed chokes, brew time stretches past 4 minutes, and the cup goes bitter and astringent. If you're using a stepped burr grinder, start at the middle of the filter range and adjust based on total brew time.</p>

<h3 class="sub-head">Bloom: 30 to 45 seconds with 2x coffee weight</h3>
<p class="body">For 15.6g of coffee, pour 31g of water in concentric circles over the bed, then wait 30 to 45 seconds. Fresh coffee should puff up and release visible CO2. If it barely moves, your beans are stale (over 4 weeks past roast date is a common cause). The bloom is the most diagnostic phase of the brew, watch it.</p>

<h3 class="sub-head">Main pour and total brew time</h3>
<p class="body">After bloom, pour in slow concentric circles from center outward, avoiding the filter walls. Pour in 2 or 3 phases for a 250g brew, letting the bed drop slightly between pours. Total brew time from first water to last drip: 3:00 to 3:30. Under 2:45 means coarser grind; over 3:45 means finer or hotter problem.</p>

<div class="callout">
  <p>The single most reliable predictor of pour-over quality is total brew time. Hit 3:00 to 3:30 with a 1:16 ratio at 200°F and you will get 80 percent of the way to the cup the bean is capable of, every time. Everything else is fine-tuning around that anchor.</p>
</div>

<h2 class="section-head">V60 vs Chemex <em>vs Kalita</em></h2>

<p class="body">The filter and dripper change the cup more than most people expect. The same beans, ratio, and temperature produce three meaningfully different drinks across the major formats. None is wrong; pick based on the cup you want.</p>

<h3 class="sub-head">Hario V60</h3>
<p class="body">Cone-shaped, single hole, ridged walls. The V60 is clarity-forward and fast-drawdown, producing the cleanest, most aroma-driven cup of the three. It rewards precise technique and punishes sloppy pours with channeling. Brew time runs 2:45 to 3:15 for 250g. Best for: Yirgacheffe, Kenya AA, light roast clarity hunting. The V60 is what specialty cafes use in competition; it's the format the picks above were calibrated for.</p>

<h3 class="sub-head">Chemex</h3>
<p class="body">Hourglass-shaped, thick bonded paper filter (20 to 30 percent heavier than V60 paper). The Chemex's thicker filter slows drawdown and strips more body, producing a cleaner but slightly more delicate cup. Brew time runs 4:00 to 5:00 for 500g (Chemex is harder to brew small). Best for: Costa Rica Tarrazu, balanced Colombians, anyone who wants a more silky mouthfeel without sacrificing clarity. The thick filter is unforgiving of stale beans.</p>

<h3 class="sub-head">Kalita Wave</h3>
<p class="body">Flat-bottomed, three small holes, ridged paper filter that creates an air gap around the bed. The Kalita's flat bottom forces even extraction regardless of pour technique, making it the most beginner-friendly of the three. Brew time runs 3:00 to 3:30 for 250g. Best for: Spirit Animal rotations, Coffee Bros. lots where you're learning the coffee, anyone whose pour is still inconsistent. The Kalita delivers 90 percent of V60 clarity with 50 percent of the skill required.</p>

<h2 class="section-head">Common mistakes that <em>ruin</em> even great coffee</h2>

<p class="body">If your pour-over tastes off and you're brewing one of the picks above, the bean is almost never the problem. The error is usually one of these five.</p>

<ul class="body-list">
  <li><strong>Stale beans:</strong> over 4 weeks past roast date is the death zone for pour-over. Beans bloom weakly, channel, and taste cardboardy. Check the bag's roast date, not the sell-by.</li>
  <li><strong>Pre-ground coffee:</strong> ground coffee loses 60 percent of its aromatic compounds in the first 15 minutes after grinding. Pre-ground from the store is dead by the time you open the bag. Buy whole bean or don't bother with pour-over.</li>
  <li><strong>Wrong grind size:</strong> too coarse produces sour, weak, under-extracted cups (brew time under 2:30). Too fine produces bitter, astringent, choked brews (brew time over 4:00). Time the brew and adjust grind, not pour speed.</li>
  <li><strong>Water temperature too low:</strong> water below 195°F under-extracts and tastes sour regardless of grind. Use a thermometer or a variable-temp kettle. Off-boil for 30 seconds gets you to roughly 200°F at sea level.</li>
  <li><strong>Skipping the bloom:</strong> pouring full water volume without the 30 to 45 second bloom traps CO2 in the bed, channels the water around the trapped gas, and produces uneven extraction. The bloom is non-negotiable.</li>
</ul>

<div class="callout">
  <p>If you change one thing today, switch from pre-ground to whole-bean and grind immediately before brewing. The difference in the cup is larger than any other single intervention, including upgrading the bean itself.</p>
</div>

